<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inverse-of-2-by-2-matrices-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Inverse of 2 by 2 Matrices I</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Determine the inverse of a 2 by 2 matrix</li>
                              <li>Solve linear equations in two unknowns using matrix method</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        8 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To engage learners in a problem-solving activity that introduces matrix inverses.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>


    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Work In Pairs</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In your pairs, write your own 2 by 2 matrix <m>M</m>. You can choose any 4 numbers (don't make them too big!) 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Choose one person to be the <term>Oracle</term> and the other to be the <term>Seeker</term>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The <term>Oracle</term> should secretly pick a vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, such as <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and compute <m>\mathbf{w} = M\mathbf{v}</m>. The <term>Oracle</term> should then share the vector <m>\mathbf{w}</m> with the <term>Seeker</term>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The <term>Seeker's</term> job is to figure out what the original vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> was, using only the information about the matrix <m>M</m> and the vector <m>\mathbf{w}</m>. Spend a few minutes trying to solve this problem.
                            </p>
                            <note component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    If Learners are struggling to find the original vector, set up a system of equations based on the matrix-vector product and encourage them to solve it using substitution or elimination.
                                </p>
                            </note>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                After a few minutes, switch roles and repeat the process with a new matrix and vector.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To connect the Learner Experience to the matrix inverse
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Do not introduce the formula for the matrix inverse yet, but familiarise Learners with its key properties.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    In the Learner Experience, we had <m>M\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{w}</m>, where we knew <m>M</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m>, and were trying to find the original vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The <term>inverse</term> of a matrix undoes the effect of a matrix, just like how closing a door is the inverse operation to opening it.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We write it as <m>M^{-1}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Applying <m>M</m> to a vector <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, and then applying <m>M^{-1}</m> will return <m>\mathbf{x}</m> to its original position: <m>M^{-1}M\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{x}</m>. Hence <m>M^{-1}M = I</m>, the identity matrix, and <m>MM^{-1} = I </m> too.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </insight>

    <note>
        <p>
            So far, we have explored what inverses do and how to verify them. In the next lesson (<xref ref="sec-inverse-of-2-by-2-matrices-ii"/>), we will develop a general formula for finding the inverse of any invertible 2 by 2 matrix.
        </p>
    </note>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <title>Undoing a Rotation</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The rotation matrix for a <m>30^\circ</m> anticlockwise turn is
                    <md>R = \begin{bmatrix} \cos 30^\circ &amp; -\sin 30^\circ \\ \sin 30^\circ &amp; \cos 30^\circ \end{bmatrix}</md>
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Verify that <m>R</m> rotates vectors by <m>30^\circ</m> anticlockwise by applying it to the vector <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What will the inverse matrix <m>R^{-1}</m> do to a vector?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Write a matrix for <m>R^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Verify your solution by finding <m>RR^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p> Calculating the product, we have:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> R \mathbf{x} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \cos 30^\circ &amp; -\sin 30^\circ \\ \sin 30^\circ &amp; \cos 30^\circ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} \cos 30^\circ \\ \sin 30^\circ \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                                <mrow> &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{3}/2 \\ 1/2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Plotting this point, we can see it is indeed a 30 degree anticlockwise rotation of the original point <m>\mathbf{x}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>R^{-1}</m> is a <m>30^\circ</m> <em>clockwise</em> rotation of a vector, undoing the effect of <m>R</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We can replace <m>30^\circ</m> with <m>-30^\circ</m> in the formula for the rotation matrix to get a matrix for <m>R^{-1}</m>, and use the fact that <m>\cos(-\theta) = \cos \theta</m> and <m>\sin(-\theta) = -\sin \theta</m> to simplify:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> R^{-1} \amp  \begin{bmatrix} \cos \left(-30^\circ\right) &amp; \sin \left(-30^\circ\right) \\ -\sin \left(-30^\circ\right) &amp; \cos \left(-30^\circ\right) \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \cos 30^\circ &amp; \sin 30^\circ \\ -\sin 30^\circ &amp; \cos 30^\circ \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                        </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Verifying by multiplication, we have
                            <md>
                                <mrow> RR^{-1} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \cos 30^\circ &amp; -\sin 30^\circ \\ \sin 30^\circ &amp; \cos 30^\circ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \cos 30^\circ &amp; \sin 30^\circ \\ -\sin 30^\circ &amp; \cos 30^\circ \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \cos^2 30^\circ + \sin^2 30^\circ &amp; \cos 30^\circ \sin 30^\circ - \sin 30^\circ \cos 30^\circ \\ \sin 30^\circ \cos 30^\circ - \cos 30^\circ \sin 30^\circ &amp; \sin^2 30^\circ + \cos^2 30^\circ \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = I </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <example>
        <title>Checking an Inverse by Multiplication</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose
                <m>M = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                and
                <m>M^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                Verify that these matrices are inverses by finding <m>MM^{-1}</m> and <m>M^{-1}M</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>MM^{-1} &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                Similarly,
                <md>
                    <mrow>M^{-1}M &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ -3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 \\ 3 &amp; 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Finding the Original Vector</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A matrix sends <m>\mathbf{x}</m> to <m>\mathbf{b}</m> by <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m>. If
                <m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ -1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                and
                <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix}</m>,
                find <m>\mathbf{x}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ -1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -6 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Compute <m>\mathbf{y} = A\mathbf{x}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>If you are given that <m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -2 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, compute <m>A^{-1}\mathbf{y}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Plot <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, <m>\mathbf{y}</m>, and <m>A^{-1}\mathbf{y}</m> on the same axes and describe what you notice.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>\mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>A^{-1}\mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \mathbf{x}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>The final point lands back on <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, showing the inverse undoes the transformation.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b}</m>. Use this idea to solve for <m>\mathbf{x}</m> when
                    <m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                    and
                    <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>


        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The matrix <m>S = \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m> flips a point across the line <m>y = x</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Describe the effect of <m>S^{-1}</m> on a point.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Hence write down <m>S^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Confirm that <m>S^{-1}S = I</m> and <m>SS^{-1} = I</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>S^{-1}</m> also flips a point across the line <m>y = x</m>, since flipping again will return the point to its original position.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>S^{-1} = S = \begin{bmatrix}0 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>S^{-1}S \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}0 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix} = I</mrow>
                                <mrow>S S^{-1} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}0 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix} = I</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <title>Undoing a Transformation</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 3 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                    and
                    <m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; -3 \\ 0 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                    Take <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and compute <m>\mathbf{y} = A\mathbf{x}</m>. Then compute <m>A^{-1}\mathbf{y}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and
                    <m>A^{-1}\mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} = \mathbf{x}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <title>Which Matrices Cannot Be Undone?</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider the matrix
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 \\ 2 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Compute <m>A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>A\begin{bmatrix} 0.5 \\ 0.25 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>What do you notice?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Explain why <m>A</m> cannot have an inverse.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>A\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> and
                                <m>A\begin{bmatrix} 0.5 \\ 0.25 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Two different vectors are sent to the same vector.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since different inputs produce the same output, the matrix <m>A^{-1}</m> (if it existed) would not be able to send the output back to <em>both</em> the original inputs. Therefore <m>A</m> has no inverse.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The scaling matrix
                    <m>S = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                    stretches the <m>x</m>-coordinate by 2 and the <m>y</m>-coordinate by 3. Write the matrix that undoes this scaling and verify that it is an inverse of <m>S</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>S^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{2} &amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp; \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix}</m>, and <m>SS^{-1} = I</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>Inverse of a Product</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let's suppose <m>S</m> represents the act of putting a shirt on, and <m>J</m> represents the act of putting a jumper on. So if <m>\mathbf{x}</m> was a person without clothes, <m>S\mathbf{x}</m> would be a person wearing a shirt.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What would <m>S^{-1}</m> and <m>J^{-1}</m> represent?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What would <m>JS</m> represent?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What effect would <m>\left(JS\right)^{-1}</m> have?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Can you guess what <m>\left(JS\right)^{-1}</m> might be in terms of <m>J^{-1}</m> and <m>S^{-1}</m>? Think carefully about the order of operations here!
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Taking off a shirt and taking off a jumper, respectively.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Putting on a shirt and then putting on a jumper. Note the order: in the expression <m>JS\mathbf{x} = J\left(S\mathbf{x}\right)</m>, we first apply <m>S</m> (putting on the shirt) to <m>\mathbf{x}</m>, <em>then</em> apply <m>J</m> (putting on the jumper).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                It would remove a jumper and a shirt
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\left(JS\right)^{-1} = S^{-1}J^{-1}</m>. To undo putting on a jumper and then a shirt, we first need to take off the jumper, and then take off the shirt.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

